/**
 * Batch 4: Docs 19-25
 * 19. User Research: Onboarding Findings (Doc)
 * 20. User Research: Power User Interviews (Doc)
 * 21. User Research: Enterprise Buyer Personas (Doc)
 * 22. API Integration Spec v2 (Doc)
 * 23. Smart Alerts Launch Checklist (Doc)
 * 24. Data Export Feature PRD (Doc)
 * 25. 2025 Annual Board Deck (Slides)
 */

function createBatch4Docs(folder) {

  // ── Doc 19: User Research: Onboarding Findings ──
  createDocInFolder("User Research: Onboarding Findings", [
    "# User Research: Onboarding Findings",
    "",
    "Researcher: Li Wei, UX Research",
    "Date: September 2025",
    "Methodology: 12 in-depth interviews (45-60 min each) + 200 survey responses (new accounts, first 30 days)",
    "Reviewed by: Sarah Chen (VP Product), Emily Rodriguez (CS Lead)",
    "",
    "## Study Objectives",
    "",
    "This study was commissioned by Sarah Chen following the Q2 2025 churn analysis, which showed 92 churn events with features (16) and competitor (20) as top reasons. Several churned accounts cited 'difficulty getting started' in their exit feedback. The objective was to understand the new user experience, identify friction points, and recommend improvements to reduce time-to-value.",
    "",
    "The study was designed to answer four questions:",
    "1. How long does it take new users to reach their first meaningful action on RavenStack?",
    "2. What features do users discover in their first 30 days, and what features remain hidden?",
    "3. How does the onboarding experience vary by industry vertical and job role?",
    "4. What would an ideal onboarding experience look like from the user's perspective?",
    "",
    "## Methodology",
    "",
    "### Interview Participants (12 total)",
    "",
    "We recruited 12 participants who created RavenStack accounts within the last 60 days. Recruitment criteria: minimum 3 logins per week, using at least 3 features. We intentionally recruited across verticals and tiers to capture a range of experiences.",
    "",
    "Participant breakdown:",
    "- DevTools: 3 participants (2 Enterprise, 1 Pro)",
    "- FinTech: 3 participants (2 Enterprise, 1 Basic)",
    "- Cybersecurity: 2 participants (1 Enterprise, 1 Pro)",
    "- HealthTech: 2 participants (1 Enterprise, 1 Basic)",
    "- EdTech: 2 participants (1 Pro, 1 Basic)",
    "",
    "Role breakdown: 4 engineering managers, 3 product managers, 2 project managers, 2 directors of operations, 1 VP of engineering.",
    "",
    "### Survey (200 responses)",
    "",
    "A 15-question survey was distributed via in-app notification to all accounts created in July-August 2025. Response rate: 42% (200 of 478 eligible accounts). Survey covered: time to first meaningful action, feature discovery, satisfaction with setup process, and likelihood to recommend.",
    "",
    "## Key Finding 1: Time-to-Value is Too Long",
    "",
    "Average time from signup to first meaningful action: 45 minutes. A 'meaningful action' was defined as: creating a project, uploading a document, sending a chat message, or completing a task. Competitors (AcmeSaaS) achieve this in 15 minutes based on their published case studies and our mystery shopping exercise conducted in August.",
    "",
    "The 45-minute average masks significant variation:",
    "- Engineering managers (DevTools, Cybersecurity): 30 minutes average — they are technical and self-sufficient",
    "- Product managers (FinTech, EdTech): 45 minutes average — they explore more features before taking action",
    "- Directors and VPs (HealthTech, FinTech): 60 minutes average — they want to configure the workspace for their team before individual use",
    "",
    "Six of 12 interviewees mentioned feeling 'overwhelmed' by the initial dashboard. The specific feedback was that the dashboard presents all 40 features in the sidebar navigation without any guidance on where to start. RavenStack has 40 features — more than any competitor — but this breadth becomes a liability when users cannot find the 3-4 features most relevant to their role.",
    "",
    "Our signup data shows 500 total accounts with 97 trial accounts. While trial-to-paid conversion is 100%, several interviewees noted they almost abandoned during onboarding.",
    "",
    "Verbatim quotes:",
    "- Participant 3 (DevTools, Enterprise, Eng Manager): 'I signed up because my DevTools team needed sprint planning, but it took me 20 minutes to even find the Sprint Planning feature. It was buried under Project Management in the sidebar, and I kept clicking on Kanban Board first because it was more visible.'",
    "- Participant 7 (FinTech, Enterprise, PM): 'I knew the product had AI features because the sales rep demo'd AI Search. But when I logged in, I couldn't find anything labeled AI. Turns out it was in Settings under Beta Features. That is not where I expected to look.'",
    "- Participant 11 (HealthTech, Enterprise, Director): 'My first priority was setting up Approval Workflows for our compliance process. It took me 45 minutes just to find and configure the first workflow. The documentation was thin and the UI did not guide me through the setup steps.'",
    "",
    "## Key Finding 2: Feature Discovery is Poor",
    "",
    "RavenStack has 40 features, but average users discover only 8-10 in their first month. The survey data shows:",
    "- Week 1: users discover 4-5 features on average",
    "- Week 2-3: users discover 2-3 additional features",
    "- Week 4+: feature discovery plateaus",
    "",
    "Top-used features (Inbox Zero at 3,606 uses, Notification Center at 3,463) are found easily because they are in the main navigation and activate automatically. Features like Stakeholder Map (3,189 uses), Risk Register (2,489 uses), and Budget Tracker (2,534 uses) are buried in sub-menus under 'Planning' and 'Governance.' Users who need these features have to actively search for them.",
    "",
    "The feature discovery problem is particularly acute for AI features:",
    "- AI Search (492 beta uses): hidden behind Settings → Beta Features toggle. 5 of 12 interviewees did not know AI Search existed until we mentioned it.",
    "- AI Copilot (376 beta uses): accessible via a small robot icon in the bottom-right corner. 3 interviewees noticed it but assumed it was a help chatbot, not an AI assistant.",
    "- AI Summary (356 beta uses): only appears when you open a document and click the '...' menu. No interviewee discovered this independently.",
    "",
    "This is a significant missed opportunity. AI features could be a key differentiator (and are a top request from power users), but new users cannot find them.",
    "",
    "## Key Finding 3: Role-Based Setup is Missing",
    "",
    "Interviewees from different verticals wanted very different initial configurations. Currently, all users see the same default workspace regardless of their role or industry.",
    "",
    "What users wanted by vertical and role:",
    "",
    "### FinTech users (37 Enterprise accounts in total)",
    "- First thing they want: Dashboard Builder and Custom Reports set up with financial metrics templates",
    "- Second: Approval Workflows for compliance sign-offs",
    "- Third: Audit Logs enabled by default (regulatory requirement)",
    "- What they do not need initially: Kanban Board, Sprint Planning, Gantt Charts",
    "",
    "### DevTools users (35 Enterprise accounts in total)",
    "- First thing they want: Sprint Planning and Kanban Board connected to their GitHub repositories",
    "- Second: Real-time Chat for standup discussions",
    "- Third: OKR Tracker linked to sprint metrics",
    "- What they do not need initially: Budget Tracker, Stakeholder Map, Client Portal",
    "",
    "### HealthTech users (27 Enterprise accounts in total)",
    "- First thing they want: Approval Workflows with multi-level approval chains",
    "- Second: Audit Logs with exportable compliance reports",
    "- Third: Document Editor with version tracking for regulatory documents",
    "- What they do not need initially: AI features (cannot use until HIPAA-compliant), Video Conferencing, Guest Access",
    "",
    "### Cybersecurity users (31 Enterprise accounts)",
    "- First: SSO Integration and security configuration",
    "- Second: Sprint Planning for vulnerability tracking sprints",
    "- Third: Risk Register for threat management",
    "",
    "### EdTech users (24 Enterprise accounts)",
    "- First: Team Spaces for organizing by department or course",
    "- Second: File Sharing and Document Editor for curriculum materials",
    "- Third: Calendar Sync for academic schedules",
    "",
    "## Key Finding 4: Integration Setup is a Friction Point",
    "",
    "Integrations Hub is the 3rd most-used feature (3,457 uses) but 8 of 12 interviewees struggled to set up their first integration. The friction points:",
    "",
    "1. Finding the integration page: Integrations Hub is in Settings → Workspace → Integrations. Users expected it to be a top-level navigation item given its importance.",
    "2. OAuth flow confusion: 5 of 12 interviewees were confused by the OAuth authorization screen ('Why does RavenStack need write access to my GitHub?'). Better explanatory text is needed.",
    "3. Configuration complexity: After connecting an integration, users need to configure which repositories/projects/channels to sync. The configuration UI uses technical terminology (webhooks, event types, payload formats) that non-technical users found intimidating.",
    "4. No guided setup: Unlike competitors who offer step-by-step integration wizards, our integration setup is a single form with many fields.",
    "",
    "API Webhooks documentation was cited as 'confusing' by 5 participants. One participant (DevTools, Enterprise) said: 'I have been a developer for 15 years, and I could not understand your webhook documentation. That is a bad sign.'",
    "",
    "## Key Finding 5: Survey Results Confirm Interview Themes",
    "",
    "The 200-response survey quantified the interview findings:",
    "- 62% rated the initial setup experience as 'somewhat difficult' or 'very difficult'",
    "- 78% said they discovered fewer features than expected in their first week",
    "- 45% did not know AI features were available",
    "- 88% would use a guided onboarding wizard if offered",
    "- Net Promoter Score for onboarding experience: 22 (below the SaaS benchmark of 40)",
    "",
    "## Recommendations",
    "",
    "### Recommendation 1: Role-Based Onboarding Wizard",
    "Implement a 4-step onboarding wizard that asks the user their role (PM, Engineer, Designer, Executive), vertical (FinTech, DevTools, etc.), and top 3 priorities. Then configure the workspace with the most relevant features surfaced and the sidebar reorganized by priority. Estimated effort: 3 sprints.",
    "",
    "### Recommendation 2: Interactive Product Tour",
    "Create a clickable product tour that highlights top features for each role. The tour should last 5-7 minutes and end with the user completing their first meaningful action. This directly addresses the 45-minute time-to-value problem. Estimated effort: 2 sprints.",
    "",
    "### Recommendation 3: Redesign Integration Setup Flow",
    "Replace the current single-form integration setup with a step-by-step wizard that explains each configuration option in plain language. Include 'Connect in 60 seconds' quick-start guides for the top 5 integrations (GitHub, Slack, Jira, Salesforce, Google Workspace). Estimated effort: 2 sprints.",
    "",
    "### Recommendation 4: Surface AI Features",
    "Move AI features out of Settings → Beta and into the main navigation. Add an 'AI' section in the sidebar with AI Search, AI Copilot, AI Summary, Smart Alerts, and AI Agent Builder. Even while in beta, these should be visible and clearly labeled as beta. Estimated effort: 1 sprint.",
    "",
    "### Recommendation 5: Contextual Tooltips",
    "Add contextual tooltips for features with fewer than 1,000 uses (indicating low discovery). Tooltips should appear on first visit and explain what the feature does, who it is for, and how to get started. Estimated effort: 1 sprint.",
    "",
    "### Target Outcome",
    "Reduce time-to-value from 45 minutes to under 20 minutes by Q1 2026. Increase first-month feature discovery from 8-10 features to 15+ features. Improve onboarding NPS from 22 to 40+."
  ].join("\n"), folder);


  // ── Doc 20: User Research: Power User Interviews ──
  createDocInFolder("User Research: Power User Interviews", [
    "# User Research: Power User Interviews",
    "",
    "Researcher: Li Wei, UX Research",
    "Date: November 2025",
    "Methodology: 8 in-depth interviews (60-75 min each) with users who used 15+ features in the last 90 days",
    "Reviewed by: Sarah Chen (VP Product), Jake Morrison (Eng Lead)",
    "",
    "## Study Objectives",
    "",
    "Power users are RavenStack's most engaged customers. They use more features, generate more usage data, and — critically — drive team adoption within their organizations. Understanding their workflows, pain points, and unmet needs is essential for retention strategy, feature prioritization, and the product's evolution toward an AI-powered platform.",
    "",
    "This study was commissioned by Sarah Chen as part of the Q4 2025 product planning process. It complements the Onboarding Findings study (September 2025), which focused on new users. Together, the two studies provide a complete view of the user experience from first sign-up to expert-level usage.",
    "",
    "## Profile of Power Users",
    "",
    "Power users were defined as accounts with 15+ features used in the last 90 days. Out of 500 total accounts, approximately 45 qualify (9%). These accounts have the lowest churn rate of any segment — below 5% annual — and the highest engagement scores.",
    "",
    "### Interview Participants (8 total)",
    "",
    "- P1: Engineering VP at a DevTools company, Enterprise tier, 22 seats. Uses 28 features.",
    "- P2: Product Lead at a FinTech company, Enterprise tier, 35 seats. Uses 24 features.",
    "- P3: Security Team Lead at a Cybersecurity company, Enterprise tier, 18 seats. Uses 21 features.",
    "- P4: Eng Manager at a DevTools company, Enterprise tier, 14 seats. Uses 23 features.",
    "- P5: Product Manager at a FinTech company, Pro tier, 12 seats. Uses 23 features.",
    "- P6: CTO at a DevTools startup, Enterprise tier, 20 seats. Uses 26 features.",
    "- P7: Operations Director at a Cybersecurity company, Enterprise tier, 16 seats. Uses 18 features.",
    "- P8: Program Manager at a HealthTech company, Pro tier, 10 seats. Uses 21 features.",
    "",
    "Power users average 23 features used (out of 40 available). They skew Enterprise tier (6 of 8 interviewed). Industries: DevTools (3), FinTech (2), Cybersecurity (2), HealthTech (1). No EdTech power users met the criteria — this is notable and may indicate a product-market fit issue in the EdTech vertical.",
    "",
    "## Key Finding 1: Power Users Drive Team Adoption",
    "",
    "Each power user has brought an average of 4.2 additional team members into active usage. They serve as internal champions — a finding that supports our land-and-expand strategy. The mechanism is consistent across all 8 participants: the power user discovers a feature, integrates it into their workflow, then shows teammates how to use it.",
    "",
    "Verbatim quotes:",
    "- P1 (DevTools, Enterprise): 'I started with Sprint Planning and Kanban Board. Within a month, I had my entire team using OKR Tracker and Document Editor. Now I am pushing them to try AI Search. Once one person on the team starts using a feature, it spreads virally because everyone sees it in their project views.'",
    "- P2 (FinTech, Enterprise): 'I brought RavenStack to my company. Started with a 5-seat Basic plan to prove it worked for our compliance workflow. Within 3 months, we were at 35 Enterprise seats. The upgrade happened because Approval Workflows solved a problem that affected every team, not just mine.'",
    "- P6 (DevTools, Enterprise): 'I am basically the RavenStack admin for our company. I set up the integrations, configured the workflows, and trained the team. I do not mind — the product is good enough that I want everyone using it. But I wish the admin experience were easier.'",
    "",
    "This finding has direct implications for the Churn Reduction Initiative: if we can identify and support power users proactively, they will drive retention organically. The Customer Health Score Framework should include a 'power user count' metric as an indicator of account health.",
    "",
    "## Key Finding 2: AI Features Are the Top Request",
    "",
    "Seven of 8 power users are currently using at least one beta AI feature. AI Search (492 total beta uses across all accounts) is the overwhelming favorite, used by all 7 AI-active participants. AI Copilot (376 uses) is used by 5 participants. AI Agent Builder (367 uses) is used by 3 participants, all of whom are Enterprise.",
    "",
    "Power users want AI Copilot to improve — the current 7.2% error rate is 'frustrating but the potential is obvious.' The key distinction between power users and regular users (from the onboarding study) is tolerance: power users understand that beta means imperfect, while regular users expect production quality.",
    "",
    "Verbatim quotes:",
    "- P2 (FinTech, Enterprise): 'AI Search already saves me 30 minutes a day finding documents. It is the single most valuable feature in the product. If AI Copilot actually worked reliably, it would save me 2 hours. I would pay more for a reliable AI Copilot.'",
    "- P4 (DevTools, Enterprise): 'I tried AI Agent Builder to automate our sprint review process. The concept is brilliant — I built an agent that pulls sprint velocity data, compares it to OKR targets, and generates a summary. It works about 70% of the time. When it works, it is magic. When it does not, the error messages are unhelpful.'",
    "- P3 (Cybersecurity, Enterprise): 'Smart Alerts is the feature I want most but cannot rely on. The 7.4% error rate means I get false alerts several times a week. I have started ignoring them, which defeats the purpose. Fix the false positive rate and I will make Smart Alerts mandatory for my entire team.'",
    "- P8 (HealthTech, Pro): 'I cannot use AI features at all because our compliance team says they are not HIPAA-compliant. I am dying to try AI Search — I saw a demo from your sales team and it would transform how our clinical documentation team works. Please prioritize HIPAA for AI features.'",
    "",
    "## Key Finding 3: Cross-Feature Workflows Matter",
    "",
    "Power users create workflows spanning multiple features. This is a distinctive behavior not seen in regular users, who tend to use features in isolation. The most common cross-feature workflows:",
    "",
    "### Engineering workflow (DevTools accounts)",
    "Sprint Planning → OKR Tracker → Dashboard Builder → Data Export",
    "The engineer creates sprints in Sprint Planning, links them to OKRs, monitors progress in Dashboard Builder, and exports weekly status reports via Data Export. This is the most common 4-feature chain we observed.",
    "",
    "### Client-facing workflow (FinTech and Cybersecurity accounts)",
    "Document Editor → Approval Workflows → Client Portal → Notification Center",
    "Teams draft documents in Document Editor, route them through Approval Workflows for compliance sign-off, publish to Client Portal for external stakeholder review, and use Notification Center to track when stakeholders view the documents.",
    "",
    "### Team management workflow (all verticals)",
    "Meeting Notes → Task Automation → Notification Center → Inbox Zero",
    "After meetings, action items are captured in Meeting Notes, which trigger Task Automation to create tasks and assign them to team members. Notification Center alerts assignees, and Inbox Zero helps them track their pending actions.",
    "",
    "### AI-enhanced workflow (early adopter accounts)",
    "AI Search → Document Editor → AI Summary → Data Export",
    "Users find relevant documents with AI Search, edit them in Document Editor, generate summaries with AI Summary, and export the summaries for stakeholder distribution. This workflow is still emerging but was described by 3 participants as their 'dream state.'",
    "",
    "The cross-feature workflow insight has a critical implication: feature-to-feature linking is weak. Users must manually navigate between features for each step. They want better automation: 'When I complete a sprint, automatically update my OKR progress and generate a dashboard snapshot.'",
    "",
    "## Key Finding 4: Data Export Needs Enhancement",
    "",
    "Data Export (3,306 uses across all accounts in 2025) is heavily used by power users for reporting. All 8 participants use Data Export at least weekly. The current limitation is that it only supports CSV format.",
    "",
    "All 8 requested JSON export for integration with their BI tools (Tableau, Looker, PowerBI) and data warehouses (Snowflake, BigQuery). Three users have built custom Python or Node.js scripts to parse CSV exports into JSON — a clear signal that we should build this natively.",
    "",
    "Specific requests:",
    "- P1: 'I want an API endpoint that lets me pull data on a schedule. Our data team wants RavenStack data in Snowflake for cross-platform analysis.'",
    "- P2: 'JSON export is the minimum. Ideally I want GraphQL access to query exactly the fields I need.'",
    "- P5: 'I export to CSV every Monday morning and then spend 20 minutes reformatting it for my executive report. If it came out as formatted XLSX with our branding, I would save an hour per week.'",
    "- P6: 'I built a cron job that downloads the CSV export via a headless browser, converts it to JSON, and loads it into our data warehouse. This is fragile and breaks whenever you update the export page. Please give me a real API.'",
    "",
    "This feedback directly informed the Data Export Feature PRD (written by Sarah Chen in December 2025).",
    "",
    "## Key Finding 5: Admin Experience is Underdeveloped",
    "",
    "Power users often serve as the de facto RavenStack administrator for their organization. They configure integrations, manage permissions, set up workflows, and troubleshoot issues for their teammates. However, the admin experience is not designed for this role.",
    "",
    "Specific pain points:",
    "- No admin dashboard: admins cannot see a bird's-eye view of their organization's usage, feature adoption, or active users.",
    "- Permission management is per-feature: changing a team member's access requires navigating to each feature's settings individually. There is no central permission management screen.",
    "- No audit view for admins: Audit Logs (2,312 uses) tracks system events, but admins want a human-readable activity feed showing 'who did what, when.'",
    "- No bulk operations: adding 10 team members requires 10 individual invitations. No CSV upload or bulk invite.",
    "",
    "## Recommendations",
    "",
    "### Recommendation 1: Power User Dashboard",
    "Create a 'Power User' dashboard showing cross-feature usage patterns, team activity, and adoption metrics. This serves the admin use case and also helps power users demonstrate RavenStack's value to their leadership (supporting renewal and expansion conversations). Estimated effort: 3 sprints.",
    "",
    "### Recommendation 2: Workflow Templates",
    "Build pre-built workflow templates connecting top feature combinations (the 4 cross-feature chains documented above). Users should be able to activate an 'Engineering Sprint Workflow' template that automatically configures Sprint Planning → OKR Tracker → Dashboard Builder → Data Export. Estimated effort: 4 sprints.",
    "",
    "### Recommendation 3: Data Export v2",
    "Prioritize Data Export v2 (JSON + API) — clear demand signal from all 8 participants. See the Data Export Feature PRD for detailed requirements. Target: April 2026 GA.",
    "",
    "### Recommendation 4: Power User Referral Program",
    "Implement a referral program that rewards power users who drive team adoption. They already do this organically (4.2 new users per power user on average), so formalizing it with incentives (credits, feature early access, RavenStack swag) could accelerate the effect. Estimated effort: 2 sprints.",
    "",
    "### Recommendation 5: Admin Console v1",
    "Build a centralized admin console with organization-level usage dashboard, bulk user management, centralized permission control, and activity feed. This addresses the top pain point for power users in admin roles. Estimated effort: 5 sprints."
  ].join("\n"), folder);


  // ── Doc 21: User Research: Enterprise Buyer Personas ──
  createDocInFolder("User Research: Enterprise Buyer Personas", [
    "# User Research: Enterprise Buyer Personas",
    "",
    "Researchers: Li Wei (UX Research) + Marcus Rivera (Product Strategy)",
    "Date: October 2025",
    "Methodology: 15 semi-structured interviews with Enterprise decision-makers across all 5 verticals",
    "Reviewed by: Sarah Chen (VP Product), David Kim (Sales Lead)",
    "",
    "## Study Objectives",
    "",
    "Enterprise accounts represent 154 of 500 total accounts but generate $1,652,695 of $2,273,427 total MRR (72.7%). Understanding Enterprise buyer personas — who they are, what they need, and how they make purchasing decisions — is critical for reducing Enterprise churn (the most financially damaging churn) and growing Enterprise revenue.",
    "",
    "This study was co-sponsored by Sarah Chen (product) and David Kim (sales). The goal was to create actionable personas that inform three workstreams: product roadmap prioritization, sales enablement materials, and customer success playbooks. Each persona should answer: who is this person, what do they need from RavenStack, what are their objections, and how do they measure success?",
    "",
    "## Methodology",
    "",
    "We interviewed 15 Enterprise decision-makers across all 5 verticals. Participants were selected based on two criteria: they had authority over the RavenStack purchase decision, and their account had been active for at least 6 months (ensuring they had enough experience to provide substantive feedback).",
    "",
    "Interview breakdown by vertical:",
    "- DevTools: 4 participants (from accounts with 14-22 seats)",
    "- FinTech: 4 participants (from accounts with 10-35 seats)",
    "- Cybersecurity: 3 participants (from accounts with 16-20 seats)",
    "- HealthTech: 2 participants (from accounts with 12-20 seats)",
    "- EdTech: 2 participants (from accounts with 10-15 seats)",
    "",
    "## Persona 1: The Engineering VP (DevTools & Cybersecurity)",
    "",
    "### Demographics",
    "35 DevTools + 31 Cybersecurity Enterprise accounts = 66 accounts (43% of Enterprise base)",
    "",
    "### Profile",
    "This persona is typically a VP of Engineering or Director of Engineering at a mid-market SaaS company (100-500 employees). They manage 3-8 engineering teams and are responsible for engineering productivity, delivery velocity, and team tooling. They report to the CTO or CEO and are evaluated on: sprint completion rates, deployment frequency, incident response time, and team satisfaction.",
    "",
    "They are technically sophisticated, value developer experience above all else, and are skeptical of tools that add process overhead without clear productivity gains. They compare RavenStack to dedicated engineering tools (Linear, Jira, GitHub Projects) rather than to general collaboration tools.",
    "",
    "### Key Needs",
    "- Sprint Planning with git integration (this is the #1 request from this persona — they want sprint boards that update from GitHub/GitLab activity)",
    "- Kanban Board with WIP limits and cycle time tracking",
    "- API Webhooks for connecting to CI/CD pipelines and internal tools",
    "- SSO Integration for single sign-on across the engineering toolchain",
    "- OKR Tracker for aligning engineering work to company goals",
    "",
    "### Buying Criteria (ranked by importance)",
    "1. Security certifications (SOC 2 Type II is the minimum bar for this persona)",
    "2. Integration depth (GitHub, GitLab, Slack, Jira bidirectional sync)",
    "3. Developer experience (keyboard shortcuts, CLI access, API-first design)",
    "4. Pricing (compared to Jira + Slack + Notion bundle, not to other collaboration platforms)",
    "",
    "### Budget and Deal Size",
    "Typical deployment: $199/seat x 20-40 seats = $3,980-$7,960/month MRR",
    "Budget authority: usually has discretionary budget up to $50K/year for tools. Above that, CTO approval required.",
    "Sales cycle: 30-45 days for initial purchase, 60-90 days for expansion.",
    "",
    "### Pain Points (Verbatim Quotes)",
    "- 'We need SOC 2 Type II before we can expand from 14 seats to company-wide. My security team will not approve it without the cert.' (DevTools, 14 seats)",
    "- 'The Sprint Planning feature is good but not great. I want it to pull data from our GitHub repos automatically. Right now my team updates it manually, which feels like double entry.' (DevTools, 22 seats)",
    "- 'AI features are exciting but I need them to be GA before I roll them out to my team. Beta features create uncertainty in my planning.' (Cybersecurity, 18 seats)",
    "",
    "### Churn Risk Factors",
    "- NimbusApp is the primary competitive threat for this persona (purpose-built for engineering teams)",
    "- Lack of SOC 2 certification is a hard blocker for expansion in regulated DevTools companies",
    "- If engineering-specific features fall behind dedicated tools (Linear, Jira), this persona will supplement or replace RavenStack",
    "",
    "## Persona 2: The Product Leader (FinTech & EdTech)",
    "",
    "### Demographics",
    "37 FinTech + 24 EdTech Enterprise accounts = 61 accounts (40% of Enterprise base)",
    "",
    "### Profile",
    "This persona is typically a VP of Product, Director of Product, or Head of Product at a company that builds technology for financial services or education. They manage 2-5 product teams and are responsible for product strategy, roadmap execution, and stakeholder communication. They report to the CEO or COO and are evaluated on: feature delivery, customer adoption metrics, NPS, and revenue contribution.",
    "",
    "They are strategic thinkers who value data-driven decision-making, executive reporting, and cross-functional visibility. They compare RavenStack to product management tools (Productboard, Aha!, Notion) and analytics platforms (Amplitude, Mixpanel) rather than to engineering tools.",
    "",
    "### Key Needs",
    "- Dashboard Builder with customizable KPI widgets and real-time data refresh",
    "- Custom Reports for board presentations and investor updates",
    "- OKR Tracker for company-to-team cascading goal alignment",
    "- Portfolio View for managing multiple products or product lines",
    "- Data Export for feeding RavenStack data into BI tools",
    "",
    "### Buying Criteria",
    "1. Analytics depth (ability to build custom dashboards without engineering help)",
    "2. Roadmap planning (visual timeline with dependencies and milestones)",
    "3. Executive reporting (one-click reports for board meetings and investor updates)",
    "4. Team visibility (cross-team view of all active projects and their status)",
    "",
    "### Budget and Deal Size",
    "Typical deployment: $199/seat x 15-30 seats = $2,985-$5,970/month MRR",
    "Budget authority: usually has discretionary budget up to $30K/year. Larger purchases require CFO approval (especially in FinTech where compliance review adds time).",
    "Sales cycle: 45-60 days (longer due to compliance and procurement processes in FinTech).",
    "",
    "### Pain Points (Verbatim Quotes)",
    "- 'I need to generate board-ready reports from RavenStack data without manual export and reformatting. Right now it takes me 3 hours every quarter. That is 12 hours per year spent on a task that should be automated.' (FinTech, 15 seats)",
    "- 'Our investors want to see product metrics in a specific format. The Dashboard Builder is close but the export options are too limited — I need PDF export with our company branding.' (EdTech, 12 seats)",
    "- 'I wish the OKR Tracker showed me which OKRs are connected to which features and which sprint items. The alignment is all manual right now.' (FinTech, 35 seats)",
    "",
    "### Churn Risk Factors",
    "- AcmeSaaS is the primary competitive threat (stronger BI and reporting capabilities)",
    "- Data Export limitations (CSV only) frustrate this persona more than any other",
    "- If analytics depth does not improve, this persona will add a dedicated BI tool and reduce RavenStack to a project management tool (lower tier, lower MRR)",
    "",
    "## Persona 3: The Operations Director (HealthTech)",
    "",
    "### Demographics",
    "27 HealthTech Enterprise accounts (18% of Enterprise base)",
    "",
    "### Profile",
    "This persona is typically a Director of Operations, VP of Clinical Operations, or Compliance Officer at a healthcare technology company. They manage cross-functional processes involving clinical, regulatory, and technology teams. They report to the COO or CEO and are evaluated on: regulatory compliance, process efficiency, audit readiness, and team coordination.",
    "",
    "They are process-oriented, risk-averse, and highly compliance-focused. They compare RavenStack to workflow management tools (ServiceNow, Salesforce Service Cloud) and compliance platforms (Drata, Vanta) rather than to general collaboration tools.",
    "",
    "### Key Needs",
    "- Approval Workflows with multi-level, configurable approval chains (3,319 total uses — 7th most-used feature)",
    "- Audit Logs with comprehensive logging and export for regulatory audits (2,312 total uses)",
    "- Time Tracking for employee hours on regulated projects (2,670 uses)",
    "- Document Editor with version history and diff view for regulatory documents",
    "- Compliance features: data residency controls, access management, retention policies",
    "",
    "### Buying Criteria",
    "1. HIPAA compliance (hard requirement — non-negotiable for HealthTech)",
    "2. Audit trail completeness (every action must be logged and exportable)",
    "3. Approval chain flexibility (sequential, parallel, and conditional approvals)",
    "4. Data security (encryption, access controls, penetration testing results)",
    "",
    "### Budget and Deal Size",
    "Typical deployment: $199/seat x 15-25 seats = $2,985-$4,975/month MRR",
    "Budget authority: usually requires both operations budget and IT security budget approval. Dual-approval makes the sales cycle longer.",
    "Sales cycle: 60-90 days (includes security review, legal contract, and compliance checklist).",
    "",
    "### Pain Points (Verbatim Quotes)",
    "- 'We cannot use AI features until they are HIPAA-compliant. But we are excited about AI Search — our clinical documentation team searches through 500+ documents daily. If AI Search is HIPAA-certified, we would roll it out to our entire organization immediately.' (HealthTech, 20 seats)",
    "- 'The Approval Workflows feature is the reason we chose RavenStack over competitors. But we need conditional approvals — if a document contains certain keywords, it should automatically route to our legal team. Right now, approval chains are static.' (HealthTech, 15 seats)",
    "- 'We had an FDA audit last month and needed to export 6 months of Audit Logs. The export took 45 minutes and the CSV format required manual processing. We need one-click PDF audit reports.' (HealthTech, 12 seats)",
    "",
    "### Churn Risk Factors",
    "- AcmeSaaS has HIPAA certification — this is a direct competitive disadvantage for us",
    "- If HIPAA compliance is delayed beyond Q3 2026, we risk losing HealthTech accounts to AcmeSaaS",
    "- Compliance features (conditional approvals, automated audit reports) are table-stakes for this persona. Feature gaps here lead directly to feature-related churn.",
    "",
    "## Cross-Persona Insights",
    "",
    "### Shared Themes Across All Personas",
    "- All personas want AI features but have different compliance requirements. The Engineering VP wants AI for code-aware sprint planning. The Product Leader wants AI for data analysis and reporting. The Operations Director wants AI for document search and automated compliance checks.",
    "- Enterprise accounts in Germany (12) and France (9) need localized contracts and GDPR features regardless of persona. Several European participants mentioned that data residency is a procurement requirement, not a preference.",
    "- Average Enterprise account size is growing: seats range from 15-40 across all personas, with some large deployments reaching 80-150+. Growth happens when the initial use case expands to adjacent teams.",
    "- Enterprise churn is disproportionately damaging — losing one $10,732 MRR Enterprise account equals losing 12.5 Basic accounts ($859 average MRR each). Enterprise retention must be the top priority.",
    "",
    "### Persona Distribution in Sales Pipeline",
    "David Kim reviewed the current sales pipeline and estimated the persona breakdown of active Enterprise opportunities:",
    "- Engineering VP: 45% of pipeline (primarily DevTools and Cybersecurity leads)",
    "- Product Leader: 35% of pipeline (primarily FinTech and EdTech leads)",
    "- Operations Director: 20% of pipeline (primarily HealthTech leads)",
    "",
    "## Recommendations",
    "",
    "### Recommendation 1: Vertical-Specific Enterprise Landing Pages",
    "Create dedicated landing pages for each vertical that speak to the specific persona's needs, feature usage patterns, and compliance requirements. Include case studies from existing customers in each vertical. Estimated effort: 2 sprints (marketing + design collaboration).",
    "",
    "### Recommendation 2: Compliance Dashboard",
    "Build a unified compliance dashboard showing SOC 2 status, HIPAA compliance status, GDPR readiness, and ISO 27001 progress. Enterprise buyers check this during procurement. Making it self-service reduces sales cycle time. Estimated effort: 3 sprints.",
    "",
    "### Recommendation 3: Enterprise-Specific Onboarding Track",
    "Create a separate onboarding flow for Enterprise accounts that includes: security configuration wizard, integration setup with IT admin involvement, vertical-specific workspace templates, and dedicated CSM introduction call within 24 hours. Estimated effort: 3 sprints.",
    "",
    "### Recommendation 4: Dedicated CSM for High-Value Accounts",
    "Assign a dedicated CSM for all Enterprise accounts generating more than $5K MRR (approximately the top 50 accounts). This directly addresses the retention risk identified in the Churn Reduction Initiative. Emily Rodriguez's CS team currently has 6 people — at least 4 additional CSMs are needed. Estimated cost: $250K/year incremental."
  ].join("\n"), folder);


  // ── Doc 22: API Integration Spec v2 ──
  createDocInFolder("API Integration Spec v2", [
    "# RavenStack API Integration Specification v2",
    "",
    "Version: 2.0",
    "Last Updated: November 2025",
    "Author: Jake Morrison, Engineering Lead",
    "Status: In Development (target GA: Q1 2026)",
    "Reviewers: Sarah Chen (VP Product), Omar Hassan (Security Lead)",
    "",
    "## Overview",
    "",
    "The RavenStack API v2 is a comprehensive RESTful API that enables programmatic access to all platform data and functionality. It replaces the limited v1 API (which only supported read operations on projects and tasks) with full CRUD capabilities, real-time webhooks, and async data export.",
    "",
    "This specification is driven by three demand signals:",
    "1. Power user research (November 2025): all 8 interviewed power users requested API-based data access. 3 users built custom scripts to work around the CSV-only Data Export feature (3,306 uses in 2025).",
    "2. Enterprise sales pipeline: 4 active Enterprise prospects have cited API-based export as a deal requirement.",
    "3. Platform strategy: the API is the foundation for our Integration Hub expansion (targeting 50 technology partners by end of 2026, up from 8 today) and the planned SDK launch.",
    "",
    "## Authentication",
    "",
    "### OAuth 2.0",
    "",
    "The primary authentication method for third-party integrations and user-authorized access.",
    "",
    "- Authorization endpoint: https://api.ravenstack.io/oauth/authorize",
    "- Token endpoint: https://api.ravenstack.io/oauth/token",
    "- Supported grant types: authorization_code, client_credentials",
    "- Token expiry: 3600 seconds (1 hour)",
    "- Refresh token expiry: 30 days",
    "- Scopes: read, write, admin, export",
    "",
    "Example authorization request:",
    "  GET https://api.ravenstack.io/oauth/authorize",
    "    ?response_type=code",
    "    &client_id=YOUR_CLIENT_ID",
    "    &redirect_uri=https://yourapp.com/callback",
    "    &scope=read+write+export",
    "    &state=random_state_string",
    "",
    "Example token exchange request:",
    "  POST https://api.ravenstack.io/oauth/token",
    "  Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded",
    "  Body: grant_type=authorization_code&code=AUTH_CODE&redirect_uri=https://yourapp.com/callback&client_id=YOUR_CLIENT_ID&client_secret=YOUR_SECRET",
    "",
    "Example token response:",
    "  { \"access_token\": \"rs_live_abc123...\", \"token_type\": \"Bearer\", \"expires_in\": 3600, \"refresh_token\": \"rs_refresh_xyz789...\", \"scope\": \"read write export\" }",
    "",
    "### API Keys",
    "",
    "Available for Enterprise tier only. Designed for server-to-server integrations where OAuth user flow is not practical.",
    "",
    "- Generated in Settings → API → Manage Keys",
    "- Rate limit: 1,000 requests/minute per key",
    "- Header: X-RavenStack-API-Key: rs_key_your_api_key_here",
    "- Keys can be scoped to specific permissions (read-only, read-write, admin)",
    "- Keys can be rotated without downtime (both old and new key valid for 24 hours during rotation)",
    "- Maximum 10 API keys per Enterprise account",
    "",
    "## Endpoints",
    "",
    "### Projects",
    "",
    "- GET /v2/projects — List all projects (paginated, 50 per page)",
    "  - Query params: status (active|archived|all), team_id, created_after, created_before, sort (name|created_at|updated_at)",
    "  - Response: { \"data\": [...], \"pagination\": { \"page\": 1, \"per_page\": 50, \"total\": 120, \"total_pages\": 3 } }",
    "",
    "- POST /v2/projects — Create project",
    "  - Body: { \"name\": \"Q1 Sprint\", \"description\": \"...\", \"team_id\": \"team_123\", \"template\": \"sprint\" }",
    "  - Response: 201 Created with project object",
    "",
    "- GET /v2/projects/:id — Get project details including members, settings, and recent activity",
    "- PATCH /v2/projects/:id — Update project (name, description, status, settings)",
    "- DELETE /v2/projects/:id — Delete project (soft delete, recoverable for 30 days)",
    "",
    "### Tasks",
    "",
    "- GET /v2/projects/:id/tasks — List tasks with filtering",
    "  - Query params: status (open|in_progress|done|blocked), assignee_id, priority (low|medium|high|urgent), due_before, due_after, label",
    "  - Supports full-text search via q parameter",
    "",
    "- POST /v2/projects/:id/tasks — Create task",
    "  - Body: { \"title\": \"Fix login bug\", \"description\": \"...\", \"assignee_id\": \"user_456\", \"priority\": \"high\", \"due_date\": \"2026-01-15\", \"labels\": [\"bug\", \"auth\"], \"custom_fields\": { \"sprint\": \"Sprint 25\" } }",
    "",
    "- PATCH /v2/tasks/:id — Update task (any field)",
    "- DELETE /v2/tasks/:id — Delete task (soft delete)",
    "- POST /v2/tasks/:id/assign — Assign task to user",
    "  - Body: { \"assignee_id\": \"user_789\" }",
    "- POST /v2/tasks/:id/comments — Add comment to task",
    "  - Body: { \"text\": \"This is blocked by the API migration\", \"mentions\": [\"user_456\"] }",
    "",
    "### Documents",
    "",
    "- GET /v2/documents — List documents (paginated)",
    "  - Query params: project_id, created_by, type (document|spreadsheet|presentation), q (full-text search)",
    "",
    "- POST /v2/documents — Create document",
    "  - Body: { \"title\": \"Sprint Review\", \"project_id\": \"proj_123\", \"content\": \"# Sprint 24 Review\\n...\" }",
    "  - Supports Markdown content format",
    "",
    "- GET /v2/documents/:id — Get document content (Markdown or HTML format)",
    "  - Query param: format (markdown|html)",
    "- PATCH /v2/documents/:id — Update document (title, content, permissions)",
    "",
    "### Data Export (NEW in v2)",
    "",
    "The async export system addresses the top user request: programmatic data export in multiple formats.",
    "",
    "- POST /v2/export — Trigger async export",
    "  - Body: { \"type\": \"project\", \"id\": \"proj_123\", \"format\": \"json\", \"include\": [\"tasks\", \"documents\", \"comments\", \"activity\"] }",
    "  - Response: { \"job_id\": \"export_abc123\", \"status\": \"pending\", \"estimated_time_seconds\": 30 }",
    "",
    "- GET /v2/export/:jobId — Check export status",
    "  - Response: { \"job_id\": \"export_abc123\", \"status\": \"ready\", \"download_url\": \"https://...\", \"expires_at\": \"2026-01-22T...\", \"file_size_bytes\": 1048576 }",
    "",
    "- GET /v2/export/:jobId/download — Download export file (redirects to S3 signed URL)",
    "",
    "Supported formats: CSV, JSON, XLSX",
    "Max export size: 100MB (covers 99.5% of current accounts)",
    "Export files stored in S3 with 7-day expiry",
    "Rate limits for export: Basic: 10 exports/hour, Pro: 50 exports/hour, Enterprise: unlimited",
    "",
    "### Webhooks",
    "",
    "Real-time event notification system for integrations.",
    "",
    "- POST /v2/webhooks — Register webhook",
    "  - Body: { \"url\": \"https://yourapp.com/webhooks/ravenstack\", \"events\": [\"task.created\", \"task.completed\", \"document.updated\"], \"secret\": \"your_webhook_secret\" }",
    "",
    "- GET /v2/webhooks — List active webhooks",
    "- DELETE /v2/webhooks/:id — Remove webhook",
    "- POST /v2/webhooks/:id/test — Send test event to verify webhook endpoint",
    "",
    "Available events: task.created, task.updated, task.completed, task.deleted, document.created, document.updated, project.created, project.archived, member.added, member.removed, comment.created, export.completed",
    "",
    "Webhook payload format:",
    "  { \"event\": \"task.completed\", \"timestamp\": \"2025-12-06T14:30:00Z\", \"data\": { \"task_id\": \"task_123\", \"project_id\": \"proj_456\", \"completed_by\": \"user_789\", \"title\": \"Fix login bug\" }, \"signature\": \"sha256=abc...\" }",
    "",
    "Signature verification: HMAC-SHA256 of the raw payload body using the webhook secret. Always verify signatures to prevent replay attacks.",
    "",
    "## Rate Limits",
    "",
    "Rate limits are per-account, not per-key. All keys for an account share the same rate pool.",
    "",
    "- Basic tier: 100 requests/minute",
    "- Pro tier: 500 requests/minute",
    "- Enterprise tier: 1,000 requests/minute",
    "- Burst: 2x limit for 10 seconds (allows short spikes without throttling)",
    "- Rate limit headers included in every response:",
    "  - X-RateLimit-Limit: 1000",
    "  - X-RateLimit-Remaining: 847",
    "  - X-RateLimit-Reset: 1701878400 (Unix timestamp when the limit resets)",
    "",
    "When rate limited, the API returns 429 Too Many Requests with a Retry-After header in seconds.",
    "",
    "## Error Codes",
    "",
    "- 400: Bad Request — invalid parameters. Response body includes field-level error details.",
    "  - Example: { \"error\": \"validation_error\", \"details\": [{ \"field\": \"due_date\", \"message\": \"must be a future date\" }] }",
    "- 401: Unauthorized — invalid or expired token. Refresh the access token and retry.",
    "- 403: Forbidden — insufficient scope or tier restriction (e.g., Basic tier trying to use admin endpoints).",
    "- 404: Not Found — resource does not exist or user lacks permission to view it.",
    "- 409: Conflict — concurrent modification detected. Re-read the resource and retry.",
    "- 429: Too Many Requests — rate limited. Retry after the specified delay.",
    "- 500: Internal Server Error — unexpected failure. Includes a request_id for support escalation.",
    "",
    "## Pagination",
    "",
    "All list endpoints use cursor-based pagination:",
    "  GET /v2/projects?cursor=eyJpZCI6MTIzfQ&per_page=50",
    "",
    "Response includes next_cursor and prev_cursor for navigation. Cursor-based pagination is stable under concurrent modifications (unlike offset-based pagination).",
    "",
    "## SDKs",
    "",
    "Official SDKs planned for Q2 2026:",
    "- JavaScript/TypeScript (npm: @ravenstack/sdk)",
    "- Python (pip: ravenstack)",
    "- Go (go get github.com/ravenstack/ravenstack-go)",
    "",
    "Each SDK will include: typed client library, automatic token refresh, rate limit handling with exponential backoff, and webhook signature verification helpers.",
    "",
    "## Migration from v1",
    "",
    "The v1 API will remain available until December 2026 but will not receive new features. Migration steps:",
    "1. Update base URL from api.ravenstack.io/v1 to api.ravenstack.io/v2",
    "2. Update authentication to use OAuth 2.0 or API keys (v1 used basic auth)",
    "3. Update response parsing (v2 wraps all responses in a { data: ... } envelope)",
    "4. Update pagination (v2 uses cursors, v1 used page numbers)",
    "5. Test webhook signatures (v2 requires signature verification, v1 did not sign payloads)"
  ].join("\n"), folder);


  // ── Doc 23: Smart Alerts Launch Checklist ──
  createDocInFolder("Smart Alerts Launch Checklist", [
    "# Smart Alerts Launch Checklist",
    "",
    "Feature: Smart Alerts (currently in beta)",
    "Owner: Priya Patel, Data Lead",
    "Engineering Lead: Jake Morrison",
    "Design Lead: Li Wei",
    "Target GA Date: Q2 2026",
    "Current Status: Beta — 378 uses, 7.4% error rate",
    "Last Updated: December 2025",
    "",
    "## Feature Overview",
    "",
    "Smart Alerts is an AI-powered notification system that learns user behavior patterns and surfaces the most important updates proactively. Unlike traditional rule-based alerts, Smart Alerts uses machine learning to determine which events are worth notifying a user about, when to send the notification, and through which channel (in-app, email, Slack, Teams).",
    "",
    "The feature was conceived during the Q1 2025 planning process when analysis of the Notification Center (3,463 total uses by year-end, 2nd most-used feature) showed that users were overwhelmed by notification volume. The average Enterprise user receives 47 notifications per day, but click-through rate is only 12%. Smart Alerts aims to reduce notification volume by 60% while increasing click-through rate to 40%.",
    "",
    "Smart Alerts entered beta in March 2025 for Enterprise accounts. As of December 2025, it has accumulated 378 uses (defined as alert events triggered and delivered) with a 7.4% error rate. The error rate is the highest of any AI feature and is the primary blocker for GA launch.",
    "",
    "## Pre-Launch Requirements",
    "",
    "### Completed",
    "- [x] 1. Core alerting engine implemented — The ML model processes user activity, identifies important events, and generates alert candidates. Architecture: event ingestion → feature extraction → importance scoring → delivery.",
    "- [x] 2. Basic notification delivery (email + in-app) — Alerts can be delivered via email and in-app notification center. Each alert includes: event summary, relevance explanation, and one-click action button.",
    "- [x] 3. Beta launched to Enterprise tier — 154 Enterprise accounts have access. Approximately 35 unique accounts (~23% of Enterprise accounts) have tried the feature.",
    "- [x] 4. Initial telemetry and usage tracking — All alert events are logged with: trigger event, importance score, delivery channel, user action (opened/dismissed/ignored), and any errors.",
    "",
    "### Not Completed (Blockers and Requirements)",
    "",
    "- [ ] 5. Error rate below 3% (currently 7.4% — PRIMARY BLOCKER)",
    "",
    "The 7.4% error rate breaks down as follows:",
    "  - 40% false positives: alert fires when no important event occurred. Root cause: the importance scoring model has insufficient training data for low-frequency events.",
    "  - 30% wrong channel: alert is delivered to the wrong channel (e.g., email when user prefers in-app). Root cause: channel preference model has not converged for users with <30 days of history.",
    "  - 20% timing errors: alert arrives too late to be actionable (e.g., meeting reminder after the meeting started). Root cause: event processing latency in the ingestion pipeline.",
    "  - 10% content errors: alert text is garbled or references the wrong entity. Root cause: the NLP pipeline for alert text generation struggles with complex entity relationships.",
    "",
    "Jake Morrison's team is working on improvements. The same NLP pipeline improvements being made for AI Copilot (error rate reduced from 7.2% to 5.8% in staging) will benefit Smart Alerts. Estimated impact: reducing errors from 7.4% to approximately 6.0% in January 2026. Further reduction to <3% will require dedicated work on the importance scoring model, estimated at 4-6 additional sprints.",
    "",
    "- [ ] 6. False positive rate below 5% (currently ~15%)",
    "",
    "Users report approximately 15% false positive rate (alerts that fire incorrectly). The solution is twofold: improve the importance scoring model (engineering) and allow users to set sensitivity thresholds (product). The sensitivity threshold feature lets users choose between 'High sensitivity' (more alerts, some false positives) and 'Low sensitivity' (fewer alerts, minimal false positives).",
    "",
    "- [ ] 7. Alert customization UI (priority, frequency, channels)",
    "",
    "Users need to configure: which event types to monitor, alert priority levels, maximum alert frequency (e.g., no more than 5 alerts per hour), and preferred delivery channels per priority level (urgent → SMS, high → email, medium → in-app, low → digest). Li Wei has designed the UI — it is in engineering backlog for Sprint 26.",
    "",
    "- [ ] 8. Slack and Teams integration for alert delivery",
    "",
    "Currently alerts are delivered via email and in-app only. Enterprise users overwhelmingly request Slack and Microsoft Teams delivery. This requires building a Slack app and Teams app that receive webhook events from the alerting engine. Engineering estimate: 2 sprints.",
    "",
    "- [ ] 9. Load testing: support 10,000 alerts/hour per account",
    "",
    "Current capacity: approximately 2,000 alerts/hour per account. The bottleneck is the ML inference pipeline, which processes one alert candidate at a time. Jake's team is implementing batch inference to achieve 10,000/hour. Estimated: 1 sprint.",
    "",
    "- [ ] 10. Documentation: user guide, API reference, admin guide",
    "",
    "Documentation is not started. Requires: end-user guide (what Smart Alerts does, how to configure), admin guide (enabling/disabling for the organization, privacy controls), and API reference (programmatic alert management for technology partners). Estimated: 2 weeks of technical writing.",
    "",
    "- [ ] 11. Migration plan: beta users auto-upgraded to GA",
    "",
    "All 35 accounts currently using Smart Alerts beta will be automatically upgraded to GA. Their existing configurations (alert rules, channel preferences) will be preserved. Any beta-only features that are removed for GA must be communicated 30 days in advance.",
    "",
    "- [ ] 12. Pricing finalized: included in Pro and Enterprise, add-on for Basic",
    "",
    "Proposed pricing: included at no extra cost for Pro ($79/seat/month) and Enterprise ($199/seat/month). Available as a $10/seat/month add-on for Basic tier. This pricing needs approval from Sarah Chen as part of the Q1 2026 pricing review. The rationale: Smart Alerts increases platform stickiness, so including it in higher tiers drives upgrades from Basic.",
    "",
    "## Dependencies",
    "",
    "### Engineering Dependencies",
    "- AI model improvement (shared with AI Copilot — Jake's team, Sprint 25-30)",
    "- Slack integration app (Engineering team, 2 sprints, Sprint 27-28)",
    "- Teams integration app (Engineering team, 2 sprints, Sprint 29-30)",
    "- Batch inference pipeline (Infrastructure squad, 1 sprint, Sprint 26)",
    "",
    "### Product Dependencies",
    "- Pricing approval (Sarah Chen — pending Q1 2026 pricing review)",
    "- Customization UI design finalization (Li Wei — completed, in engineering backlog)",
    "- Documentation (Technical Writer — not yet assigned)",
    "",
    "### External Dependencies",
    "- Slack App Directory review (1-2 weeks after submission)",
    "- Microsoft Teams App Store review (2-4 weeks after submission)",
    "",
    "## Post-Launch Plan",
    "",
    "### Week 1-2: Monitoring Phase",
    "- Monitor error rate hourly for the first 48 hours, then daily for the remaining 12 days",
    "- Have a rollback plan ready: feature flag can disable Smart Alerts GA and revert to beta within 15 minutes",
    "- Dedicated support engineer assigned to Smart Alerts tickets for the first 2 weeks",
    "",
    "### Week 3-4: Feedback Collection",
    "- Weekly feedback review from GA users via in-app survey",
    "- Track: alert volume per user, click-through rate, dismiss rate, error reports, and NPS for the feature",
    "- Target metrics: alert volume reduced 60% vs unfiltered notifications, click-through rate 40%+, error rate <3%",
    "",
    "### Month 2-3: Iteration",
    "- Iterate on alert templates based on usage patterns",
    "- Add new event types based on user requests",
    "- Improve importance scoring model with GA usage data (larger training set)",
    "",
    "### Target Adoption",
    "- Month 1 of GA: 500 uses (up from 378 beta uses total)",
    "- Month 3 of GA: 2,000 uses",
    "- Month 6 of GA: 5,000 uses (would make it a top-15 feature by usage)",
    "",
    "## Risk Assessment",
    "",
    "- HIGH RISK: Error rate does not reach <3% by target date. Mitigation: launch with 'Low sensitivity' as default to reduce false positives, even if it means lower alert volume.",
    "- MEDIUM RISK: Slack/Teams app store review takes longer than expected. Mitigation: launch GA without Slack/Teams integration, add them as a post-GA update.",
    "- LOW RISK: User adoption is slower than expected. Mitigation: coordinate with Marketing for launch campaign and with CS for proactive Enterprise enablement."
  ].join("\n"), folder);


  // ── Doc 24: Data Export Feature PRD ──
  createDocInFolder("Data Export Feature PRD", [
    "# Product Requirements Document: Data Export v2",
    "",
    "Author: Sarah Chen, VP Product",
    "Date: December 2025",
    "Status: Approved for Q1 2026 development",
    "Priority: P1",
    "Engineering Lead: Jake Morrison",
    "Design Lead: Li Wei",
    "",
    "## Problem Statement",
    "",
    "Data Export is the 9th most-used feature (3,306 uses in 2025) but currently only supports CSV format. Enterprise customers (154 accounts, $1,652,695 MRR in December) are requesting JSON and API-based export for integration with their BI tools and data warehouses.",
    "",
    "The problem manifests in three ways:",
    "1. Manual reformatting: Users export CSV and then manually convert to JSON or XLSX for their downstream tools. Power user research (November 2025) found that 3 of 8 users built custom scripts to automate this conversion — a clear signal that we should build it natively.",
    "2. No automation: Current export requires a user to manually click 'Export' and download a file. Users want scheduled exports (daily, weekly, monthly) and API-triggered exports for pipeline integration.",
    "3. Limited scope: Current export only covers task data. Users want to export documents, project metadata, activity logs, and team metrics.",
    "",
    "This feature directly addresses the Data Export feedback from the Power User Interviews (November 2025) and is referenced in the API Integration Spec v2 (POST /v2/export endpoint).",
    "",
    "## Goals",
    "",
    "- Support JSON and XLSX export formats alongside existing CSV",
    "- Provide async API-based export for large datasets (see API Spec v2, POST /v2/export)",
    "- Enable scheduled exports (daily, weekly, monthly) with email delivery",
    "- Maintain current Data Export UX simplicity while adding power-user capabilities",
    "- Reduce manual data processing time for Enterprise users by 80%",
    "",
    "## Non-Goals",
    "",
    "- Real-time streaming export (defer to Q3 2026) — requires websocket infrastructure that is not yet in place",
    "- Direct database connectors (Snowflake, BigQuery — defer to partner program) — building native connectors is a significant effort; the API-based export is sufficient for users to build their own pipelines",
    "- Custom export templates (defer based on demand signal) — users want format control (JSON, XLSX, CSV) but have not requested custom column selection or branding in export files",
    "- Export of AI feature data (AI Search queries, AI Copilot interactions) — these have privacy implications that need separate review",
    "",
    "## User Stories",
    "",
    "### Story 1: Enterprise Admin — JSON Export for Data Warehouse",
    "As an Enterprise admin, I want to export project data as JSON so I can load it into our Snowflake data warehouse for cross-platform analysis.",
    "Acceptance criteria:",
    "- Export produces valid JSON with consistent schema",
    "- Includes all task fields, custom fields, and metadata",
    "- Handles nested data (comments, attachments) as nested JSON objects",
